<h1>2.1.3 Gender</h1>
<p>Status: <em>draft</em> discussion not finished</p>
<h2 id="relevant-postag-codes">Relevant postag codes:</h2>
<p><strong>Position and letters in postag string:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>position: <strong>7th</strong> (gender)</p></li>
<li><p>letters: <strong>m</strong> (masculine), <strong>f</strong>
(feminine), <strong>n</strong> (neuter)</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Example: n-s—<strong>m</strong>n- (noun, singular,
<strong>masculine</strong>, nominative)</p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary:</h2>
<p>Greek has three genders: masculine, feminine and neuter. The gender
of the the attributes (definite articles, adjectives, participles, most
pronouns, some numerals) agree with the gender of their head (e.g.&nbsp;the
head of the noun phrase or the referent of the personal pronoun). The
gender is assigned in some animate nouns semantically (the rule of
natural gender), but for most words morphologically as discussed by
<a data-link-newtab="" href="/smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.2.html" data-url="smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.2.html">Smyth</a> and in more detail by <span class="citation" data-cites="luraghi2013">Luraghi (2013)</span>. Verbal
finite endings do not present gender agreement with nouns (cf.&nbsp;Corbett
2013). Some adjectives have only two genders (non-neuter and neuter).
Participles inflect in all genders; like 1st (feminine) and 2nd
(masculine and neuter) declension adjectives. It must be noted that
formally masculine and neuter endings coincide in some cases in the
second declension (genitive and dative singular and plural), and the
plural genitive ending is homomorphic for all three genders.</p>
<h2 id="example-from-papygreek-corpus">Example from PapyGreek
corpus</h2>
<ol type="1">
<li>προσαγόρευε <strong>τὴν κυρείαν ἀδελφὴν μακαρείαν</strong> Ἀσοῦν καὶ
<strong>τὴν μητέραν</strong> αὐτῆς καὶ…<br>
(prosagóreue <strong>tḕn kureían adelfḕn makareían</strong> Asoûn kaì
<strong>tḕn mētéran</strong> autês kaì…)<br>
<em>Greet my blessed lady sister Asous and her mother and…</em><br>
<a href="https://new.papygreek.com/text/35155">P.Oxy.14.1774</a>, 17–19
(sent. 7), transl. <span class="citation" data-cites="bagnallcribiore">Bagnall and Cribiore (2008)</span>,
p.&nbsp;194.</li>
</ol>
<p></p><div style="height:300px; " data-treeid="1" class="sentence-tree tf-tree tf-result" data-json=""></div><p></p>
<h2 id="discussion">Discussion</h2>
<ul>
<li>Is there change in time for usage for some nouns? In later
postclassical Greek not always same as in classical? (see Horrocks,
Mayser; Gignac; Cf. Giannakis’ talk 24.2.2023 PGN)</li>
<li>Egyptian has three genders as well; differences? Sometimes
phrase-initial inflection interrupts agreement of cases, what about
gender (in Pathyris at least we have examples)?</li>
<li>multiple genders and pronouns?</li>
<li>are months masculine also in papyri, cf.&nbsp;Smyth? And countries,
islands, cities, trees, and plants feminine?</li>
<li>first and second person pronouns do not indicate gender; in
PapyGreek these are occasionally added.</li>
</ul>
